I had to cut her off and ask her if she was trying to tell me that I wasn’t able to have the reservation? Even after explaining I was vaccinated, she told me that I could not have a reservation. I have been thinking about the review I can write; to do justice towards Charleston. We were met with disdain upon entering Charleston. It was our first experience; as we never live in an area long. We were a party of four and subjugated ourselves to a drink in the bar while waiting for our reservation. We did not, personally, have an issue to wait, but the first responders acted, breathlessly, that we might not be okay. Eventually, we were told our table was ready. Our drinks would be taken to our table. We were allowed to have, in my opinion, the best table in Charleston. Charleston has an open kitchen; that is memorizing for those who admire the orchestra of a gorgeously run kitchen. The calmness. The beauty. No yelling or screaming; is it not one in the same? Our party of four ordered four courses each. Now, I will dissect. The Fresh Artichoke Soup is divine; truffle oil.  The Grilled Veal Sweetbread was soft and magical. The Pan Roasted Wild Halibut, took the breath away...the mushrooms; oysters. The Steak Tartare was luxurious. The Salad Gourmande is perhaps one of the best articles I have put in my mouth. There were missteps with the food. The Rich Lobster Soup with Curry; the pieces of lobster were overcooked. At the time, two people in my party had the Grilled Venison Tenderloin. While they were supposedly the same dishes, one of my party members said they received, little sweet potatoe puree, and too much sauce. Not consistent.  The service at Charleston is the best we have had in America. If you have a crumb on your plate, it is replaced. All dishes are explained when placed on the table. Your utensils are replaced. Your bread and water are always replenished. The personality of the staff, is what hospitality should consist of. The BEST.  Ms. Wolf, thank you for the food and experience.
Baltimore number one restaurant

The wait staff and wine pairings were lovely. We had to wait to be seated, which chafed after making a reservation. The food was hit or miss, and for the price we expected better quality and larger portions. We are accustomed to fine dining, but nevertheless we were disappointed. I spent the entire time feeling as though they were cutting corners to save money, which is not a feeling I enjoyed at what is supposed to be the best restaurant in Baltimore.  My husband got a salad which was essentially one leaf of a common varietal of romaine with some raspberries and a sprinkling of goat cheese. My asparagus salad had an interesting presentation, but there just simply wasn't enough goat cheese mousse to appreciate the contrast of flavors. His tuna tartare and my lobster soup were very good, and the portions were more appropriate. His scallop was perfectly done but uninspired (and there was literally one smallish scallop). The spring morel ravioli was lovely with a rich complex sauce. His rabbit loin and rice were very nice, but my tarbot was nothing I couldn't easily have done at home. Desserts were mediocre at best - dry flourless chocolate cake, and bland mousse. Even the complementary amuse bouches and petit fours were just okay. At the prices they command I expected better. We went for my birthday, and I doubt we'll be returning. I find myself wishing we'd gone somewhere else.  Finally, it is disappointing at a place as upscale as this that there isn't more emphasis on sustainability and responsible animal husbandry. Red snapper is known to be overfished, and veal is subject to cruelty. We make every effort to source ethical meats and seafood in our private kitchen - I would expect at least that level of effort from an award winning establishment.  I am revising my review down to one star because I was never contacted as was promised in their response below. They replied almost certainly as a public relations stunt, and not because they care two figs what I think about their restaurant. I've eaten a lot of excellent food in my lifetime so far, and I'm sorry to say it was not at this restaurant.

My mother and decided to have our November bday celebrations as one as they are only 9 days apart. My dad suggested we go here. I didn't really know what to expect as I saw the menu online and was somewhat thrown off by the option tasting menu situation. I was blown away. First of all, the portions are actually decent for a tasting type menu. You're not going to be absolutely stuffed but you aren't going to feel hungry after the light option. I have probably had better individual dishes elsewhere, but it would be hard to beat the consistency of this place. Each serving was better than the last. I thought the service was very appropriate. Seeing as the wine pairing comes with the dishes, hovering servers were not present nor needed. They were there when you needed them to be. I would imagine that were this restaurant in DC or NYC that it would no doubt be a 2 Michelin star. I also think that in terms of value for money, it doesn't get much better than this. Yes it's more expensive than your average restaurant, but it's really not that much more expensive and it is 10x better.

This is my favorite restaurant in Baltimore. It is a dining experience worth your time and attention. Worst fine dinning experience. The staff in the restaurant were transparently cold and fake. It was clear that the servers and others are not primarily interested in creating a perfect dining experience for the guests rather they are focused in selling as much as possible. They were extremely psychologically manipulative. In this they are subtle and nearly undetectable. I will share to what extent. In my case, I don’t drink alcohol, in fact I dislike it so profoundly that I certainly would never in my life order it. It is well known that in the first couple minutes of arriving to a restaurant one is the most suggestible. The sommelier comes over. With an obvious focus on raising the price of the check not on guests well being, with nothing less than trained suggestion and outright undetectable to the guest psychological manipulation moments later the next thing I knew I’ve agreed to a glass of wine. I would never have agreed to this otherwise. The server was cold and stoic. Not in a very elegant and proper manner that one might expect in perhaps an old world style fine dinning environment but rather plainly unanimated and low energy. I cannot say if he was fake in his attentions because he had a comprehensive command of his body language which revealed no negative tells but also no positive either. He certainly was not warm in demeanor. His delivery of descriptions of items on the menu and specials was not fluid and professional as one would expect in this price range of fine dinning. Rather several times he would pause and think for a while of the rest of the ingredients he was listing. His delivery was non fluid and even forgot an ingredient or two all together then had to refer to his paper in his pocket. When the sommelier would pour a wine glass then when asked about tasting notes would take a step back after saying something then another it gave the impression that he did not have sureness and confidence it what he was saying and took away credibility from his statements. When the others would come pour a wine glass then were asked about tasting notes could only come up with two words and often with noticeable difficulty and hesitation. The focus was truly on selling as much as possible and not on creating a perfect dinning experience. Another and I were both subconsciously psychologically manipulated to order 4 courses although ahead of time we both clearly had the intention and wish to order only 3, this is what would have occurred if our actual wishes took place. Most grievous of all I somehow ended up asking for a full wine pairing. I truly dislike alcohol and this led to deep despair that evening and probably years of regret. This would never have happened otherwise. There was an enormous amount of self serving, money generating amount of psychological manipulation. Some positives include good lighting, nice bathrooms, the food was good, great time spacing between courses, and very impressive food runners. The food runners were so genuine, composed, professional, and flawlessly delivered all descriptions without any hesitations. The restaurant would do fantastically if it would promote its food runners. Upon leaving, the smiles and general demeanor of the staff was so transparently disingenuous. Their actual self behind their facade was plainly visible. They were so extremely obvious that they are catering to us only because we are paying them to. Overall, the bill for our group of three was well over $600 after tip. Feel like escaping out of Baltimore to an extravagant place? Go to Charleston. Want to take out someone special for an incredible experience unlike any other? Go to Charleston.  Wow is an understatement for how good of a dinner I had last night at Charleston. I decided to take a good friend out to dinner here for her 30th birthday, and called the day of for reservations. The staff member I spoke to on the phone made sure all of my questions were answered, and took the time to go over the menu/courses with me.  SERVICE: First off, free valet parking was extremely convenient. Upon arrival, we were immediately greeted by the staff members and they wished my friend a happy birthday. Our waiter was extremely professional, and went above and beyond in describing each item on the menu. We spent approximately 2.5 hours in Charleston (be prepared spend a good amount of time here) and had prompt service the whole time we were there.  FOOD: We opted for the 3 course dinner with wine by the glass. I wish I could describe how good each meal was. Before our main courses, our waiter brought out the most delicious bread (one of which was the best cornbread I've ever had.) I started off with the lobster soup then chose truffle oil white fettuccini and then beef sirloin. Each dish was made with extreme detail and flavor. I especially loved that each time a dish was brought to her table, our waiter took the time to describe each dish and how it was prepared.  DESSERT: Man oh man the dessert was also spectacular. We were actually very full by the time we finished our third course but we couldn't resist ordering dessert considering dessert is INCLUDED with all course meals! (So don't skip dessert.) Our waiter recommended a chocolate dessert for me and each bite was to die for. Charleston also put a candle on my guest's dessert for her birthday which was thoughtful. They even brought out a separate tray of tiny dessert delicates as shown in the photo with this review.  All in all, I had the most phenomenal dining experience here. Definitely the most expensive dinner I've ever paid for but it was worth every penny. I plan on taking others here on special occasions in the near future. Thank you charleston for an out of this world dinner experience! I will never forget it.

Loved the Xs and Os Menu!! Such a great experience for Valentines Day! We also did the wine pairings and cheese course!! Loveeeeee The ambiance is very nice both comfortable but not too stuffy The service was quick to warm up to us despite unusual request The food was excellent! And as the title suggested in our small group we got to try the while menu ! The highlight were the sweat breads and the beef and an honorable mention for the polenta . Would be happy to be back!

I started with lobster soup, which was excellent, but was not the star of my meal.  Next was oysters Rockefeller that were cooked to perfection.  My favorite course was the crawfish and grits.  Interestingly this is not something I would usually order, but our waiter sold me on the shellfish’s freshness.  It was delicate, fresh and glorious.  I finished with with a light preparation of rockfish, thankfully,  that perfectly rounded out the meal.  While I’ve mostly highlighted the food,  the service was a big part of our experience. I’ve never been treated better.  We had a special appetizer and dessert sent to the table in honor of our anniversary.  Service was attentive and smart without being pretentious.  Cindy Wolf and Tony Foreman were visible and present and more personally involved in the operation than I expected.  If you want a special dining experience in Baltimore,  look no further.

Charleston is really in a class by itself in Baltimore.  There's nothing else in town like it.  No other restaurant serves food this exquisitely prepared, where every single ingredient, but also every single element of the service, the atmosphere, the decor, the wine, are so immaculately presented.  It's also the most expensive restaurant in town, but it can justifies it.  We can't afford to go regularly - we can have 3 outrageously expensive dinners elsewhere for the price of one meal at Charleston - but if someone asks "what's the best restaurant in town?" there is simply not another answer.  We've had several tremendous meals there, each time revealing something about an ingredient or a dish in a novel way that is really genius.  So many great little dishes and experiences.  The only oyster my wife has ever enjoyed.  The best mushrooms I have ever eaten. Simply incredible proteins.  Obviously Cindy Wolf knows what she is doing, given her array of great restaurants in town, but Charleston stands alone, as it enjoys her most focused attention.  It's an intimidating place given the price point and the almost hushed sense of silence and reverence you feel in the place - but our most memorable experience has more to do with NOT being gourmands than otherwise.  My wife sent back a bottle of wine that she really didn't enjoy, and the sommelier could not have been more gracious, offering up several other bottles that she also didn't enjoy.  Mind you, these were not corked, just not to her taste.  The somm was outstanding, generous and even offered to bring us wines by the glass that might be more to our (very uneducated) palates.  He proceeded to give a master class in wines; the piece de resistance was when he brought back the first (rejected) bottle (without letting us see the label), which had since had an opportunity to open up and was now properly paired with food and opened palates.  The once-rejected bottle was now a star.  Absolutely genius - probably the best experience I have ever had in a restaurant.   All done without arrogance or snootiness... just an absolutely sublime display of knowledge, graciousness, and customer service.
Simply outstanding in every respect.  One of, if not the, best restaurants in Baltimore.  Service and food are consistently spectacular.

Don't go to Charleston to eat. Go here for a dining experience. The food is all well prepared and well presented, if scant. I believe whether or not you find a particular dish or "course" exceptional or not depends on your personal taste. Two of the dishes that were highly recommended by our waiter fell short for me. One was panroasted rockfish with mushrooms, the other was shrimp and grits. For me, the rockfish was pleasant, but apparently, the waiter thought it was excellent and my husband loved it. The shrimp and grits was also unexceptional to me, I make better. Also, it consisted of one shrimp, butterflied and twisted to make a presentation, but one shrimp. The other dish that I found more than skimpy was the seviche. 4 paper thin slices of fish approximately 1/2" x 3".....ridiculous? yes.....but exceptional. I can still taste it and loved every minute bite. The sweetbreads with foie gras was also exceptional and memorable, and the lamb chop was delicious. The service was exemplary, subtle, never in your face, graceful and nothing was missed. But the true experience is the Sommelier. You would expect a restaurant that prides itself on its cellar to have an excellent sommelier. You would not be disappointed. But, to be excellent, a sommelier needs only to be deeply knowledgeable and professional, which she is. What she also is is warm, friendly, charming and beyond helpful. I learned more about wine chatting with Linah over the course of dinner than in any other time....ever. She clearly loves what she does and helps you to love it too. Without Linah, I would have been impressed with the quality of the service and presentation. With Linah, I had a delightful and memorable dining experience.

When I politely asked her what would be her solution to the issue, she replied: "I don't know, I don't have children."  My niece and nephew made the trip from London to join me for my birthday - Charleston was NOT my choice from the beginning - food is a HUGE YAWN, but I regrettably relented. We were asked to sit in the bar area for a few minutes while waiting for our table, where we each had a glass of wine.  When our table was ready, the hostess / wine sommelier approached us by name, and showed us to our table, in the back right room.  Very quiet, only about 9 tables there.  We were guided through the menu by our waitress, and each chose the 3 course dinner.  Everything was fantastic.  Also opted for a cheese course, which was awesome as well.  Dessert was great too.  The chef, Cindy Wolf, made her rounds and talked with us as well.  Everyone was professional, friendly and helpful.  Highly recommend the shrimp and grits, and the passion fruit creme brulee for dessert.  Definitely not a restaurant we will frequent (due to the cost), but we want to return soon!  We will talk about this meal and experience for a long time.
Excellent food and service!
Prices are reasonable and food is awesome. Staff looked after us very well. Highly recommended.
